A central talking point of Bolsonaro’s campaign was to market the far-right candidate as the only one who could free Brazil from the ills of corruption.
It only makes sense for the president-elect to try to disconnect his image from the corrupt politicians that voters have come to hate so intensely.
Examining Bolsonaro’s top deputies and cabinet appointments, it becomes apparent that his speeches against corruption are nothing but empty words.
Jair Bolsonaro embraces Sen. Magno Malta during a filming ceremony for the PSL party on March 7, 2018.
Like others in Bolsonaro’s inner circle, Malta has been dogged by rumors around shady dealings and a court case.